******
[2]
Date: Wed 31 Aug 2016
Source: O Globo [in Portuguese, trans. Mod. TY, edited]
http://g1-globo.com/goias/noticia/2016/08/vacinacao-contra-febre-amarela-e-reforcada-em-areas-rurais-de-catalao.html


Health officials are intensifying vaccination against yellow fever in rural properties in Catalão, in the Goiás southeast. The work will continue until December [2016] when hundreds of farms in 15 communities must be visited. According to the State Secretariat of Health (SES), this year 8 people have died, victims of the disease in the state.

The focus of the [vaccination] campaign is to immunize the population that doesn't always have access to health posts, such as the 56-year-old rural farmer, resident of Ceará, who had never been vaccinated against yellow fever. "[He had] never needed to take it because he was not at risk, but not here in this region, which has a lot of vegetation, a lot of water around and the mosquito can be close to us. Now we will be protected," he said.

Another point that concerns the populace is the abundant presence of monkeys, which can be hosts of the disease [virus]. "Thank goodness I received the vaccine and now I am relaxed," said a rural farmer.

According to SES, at the beginning of this year [2016], a rural worker from Cumari, a farm in the same region, died, a victim of yellow fever. He was a 38-year-old who lived with a family on a farm. "Everyone needs to have this vaccine against yellow fever today, since this is the main protection against the serious disease," said the coordinator of the vaccination campaign, Luciana Martins.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

[The 8 cases were confirmed and, according to the news, [there are] 6 deaths. Information on when there have been cases and deaths is conflicting -- have cases occurred between 2015-2016 or only in 2016 (as suggested by the 2nd report)? Apparently all the cases involve sylvatic [forest] transmission. Information about people-dates-places is scarce and imprecise. Anyway, the concern is: given the continuous transmission since 2015, the high case fatality, cases distributed in different regions of the state, if suspected in the capital [Goiania], the population still non-immunized ...

Additional information will be welcome. - Mod.RNA

The sylvatic transmission cycle of yellow fever virus transmission involves monkeys (the reservoir host) and forest mosquitoes. This transmission cycle occasionally spills over to humans. Dead monkeys are frequently found where sylvan transmission occurs, although there is no mention of dead monkeys here. Sylvan YF has occurred frequently in Brazil, including in Goias state. - Mod.TY

Maps of Brazil can be seen at http://s13.postimg.org/jumnalk87/map_of_Brazil.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4467679,3168. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
